    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 7th with a high-ceiling lineup led by **Yordan Alvarez** (75.76) and **Junior Caminero** (73.35), our two strongest plays of the day. **Yordan Alvarez** benefits from a massive 14% park factor boost against Freeland, and despite a slight platoon disadvantage, his elite xwOBA makes him an auto-start. Similarly, **Junior Caminero** projects well against Assad; the 19% boost from the matchup against a soft SP xERA of 4.83, combined with the premium protection of the #4 hole, cements his status as our primary RBI anchor. At the top of the order, **Colt Keith** (67.82) and **Trea Turner** (68.41) are essential, with **Colt Keith** leveraging a 10% order bonus and a favorable matchup against Bradley to provide the necessary spark for our Runs category.\n\nThe most difficult decision on today's card was bypassing **Josh Smith** (42.45), who fell just outside the optimal configuration. While his dynamic platoon edge against the RHP Kirby provides a decent floor, he ultimately couldn't displace the upside offered by **Victor Scott II** (51.62) or **Carson Benge** (50.97). We are prioritizing **Victor Scott II** specifically for his stolen base potential, which remains our primary concern in 5x5 Roto scoring; his speed is a non-negotiable asset despite the minor penalty for batting ninth. Conversely, we are keeping a close eye on **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (56.38); his massive 14% platoon boost against the right-handed Englert makes him a high-reward play, though the 3.38 SP xERA warns of a tougher path to counting stats than the raw score might suggest. We remain cautious with **Kazuma Okamoto** (43.82) and **Dillon Dingler** (46.59), as their scores hover near our bench threshold; should wind conditions shift in their respective ballparks, we will be ready to pivot to available options like **Jerar Encarnacion** or **Logan O'Hoppe** if lineup adjustments occur.",
